Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the
@rigatoni pasta{180%g}.

When boiling, add the rigatoni to the water and bring back to the boil.
Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pan.

Drizzle with @oil{} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef and pork mince{240%g} and @sliced mushrooms{80%g}
and fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Use a #spoon{} to break the mince up as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

In the meantime, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use
a #garlic press{}).

Once the mince and mushrooms are cooked, drain and discard any excess fat.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer
pink in the middle.

Add the garlic and @harissa paste{50%g} (add less if you'd prefer things milder),
stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @tomato passata{1%jar}, @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @Worcester sauce{15%ml},
@water{100%ml} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} for the sauce (see pantry for both amounts)
into the mince pan.

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the sauce has thickened,
~{5-6%minutes}.

Once the sauce has thickened, add the cooked pasta to the pan and stir to combine.

Remove the pan from the heat and stir through half the @hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated).
Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Spoon the spicy harissa beef rigatoni into your #serving bowls{}.

Sprinkle over the remaining cheese to finish. Enjoy!